00:00:23.875 --> 00:00:25.250
PROFESSOR: I'm
really sick today.

00:00:25.250 --> 00:00:27.620
And I hope I can make
it through this lecture

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:29.570
without disgracing myself.

00:00:29.570 --> 00:00:32.330
But this is a favorite
topic of mine, too,

00:00:32.330 --> 00:00:36.440
so maybe it will be OK.

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:42.020
So we're going to talk
about the helium atom, which

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:46.580
is really an amazing
thing because hydrogen--

00:00:46.580 --> 00:00:49.610
it was possible to
solve it exactly.

00:00:49.610 --> 00:00:52.780
All sorts of fantastic
things happened.

00:00:52.780 --> 00:00:57.763
And it seemed like just a small
step from hydrogen to helium.

00:00:57.763 --> 00:01:01.910
And nobody can take that step.

00:01:01.910 --> 00:01:04.489
It's entirely approximate.

00:01:04.489 --> 00:01:08.930
And you can do better and
better on the approximations,

00:01:08.930 --> 00:01:13.280
but we'd like to have some
physical sense of what's

00:01:13.280 --> 00:01:15.980
going on, and what are
the important terms,

00:01:15.980 --> 00:01:20.000
and can we steal
things from hydrogen?

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:21.980
The answer is, yeah, we can.

00:01:21.980 --> 00:01:26.150
And that was what last
lecture was mostly about.

00:01:26.150 --> 00:01:35.240
The energies for hydrogen
are minus z squared hc times

00:01:35.240 --> 00:01:38.750
the Rydberg over n squared.

00:01:38.750 --> 00:01:48.570
And we have the ionization
energy from the nth level.

00:01:48.570 --> 00:01:51.710
And so this actually
is the way we

00:01:51.710 --> 00:01:55.190
make a link to this concept
of electronegativity

00:01:55.190 --> 00:01:57.620
because the dominant
thing in electronegativity

00:01:57.620 --> 00:01:59.910
is the ionization energy.

00:01:59.910 --> 00:02:01.980
And this is the
ionization energy.

00:02:01.980 --> 00:02:07.700
And when you put them
together and solve for n,

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:14.630
you get this arrangement hc
z squared times the Rydberg

00:02:14.630 --> 00:02:18.740
over the ionization
energy, square root.

00:02:18.740 --> 00:02:23.460
That's n, or the effective
principle quantum number.

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:25.850
And then we have all
of these formulas that

00:02:25.850 --> 00:02:30.410
can be derived from
hydrogenic wave functions,

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:33.740
both for diagonal
expectation values

00:02:33.740 --> 00:02:35.960
or off diagonal matrix elements.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:37.940
They're all closed form.

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:40.160
And this is wonderful
because it then

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:47.750
enables you to use the formulas
that are obtained exactly

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:49.920
for hydrogenic wave functions.

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:57.170
And so if we know the dependence
of an electronic property on n

00:02:57.170 --> 00:03:00.140
and l--

00:03:00.140 --> 00:03:03.260
well, n is experimentally
determined--

00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:04.740
distance real ionization.

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:08.210
l is determined from
angular momentum.

00:03:08.210 --> 00:03:13.980
Then we can determine the
expected scaling of everything

00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:15.800
on the quantum numbers.

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:18.620
And even if that's
wrong, it tells you

00:03:18.620 --> 00:03:23.390
the qualitative effects when you
get to more complicated systems

00:03:23.390 --> 00:03:24.800
in one electron atoms.

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:28.510
And this is really what
I meant by structure,

00:03:28.510 --> 00:03:34.350
where everything is related
to basically one observation.

00:03:34.350 --> 00:03:37.920
There is one other thing
that I didn't stress.

00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:45.480
And it's another concept from
5.112., and that's shielding.

00:03:45.480 --> 00:03:48.390
So suppose we have
a sodium atom.

00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:53.800
Most of the electrons
are in a compact core.

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:57.730
The outer electron
sees a charge of 1,

00:03:57.730 --> 00:04:02.580
even though the charge on
the nucleus is larger than 1.

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:09.400
And if you ask, well, suppose
we look at this in a region,

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:14.230
and we have an
electron inside of it,

00:04:14.230 --> 00:04:16.209
the charge that
that electron sees

00:04:16.209 --> 00:04:21.160
is the amount of electrons
inside the sphere defined

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:23.570
by this radius.

00:04:23.570 --> 00:04:29.320
And so the z, we can
call it the z effective,

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:31.720
is a function of r.

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.300
And you have a different
function every o.

00:04:34.300 --> 00:04:37.105
And so it's a way of
putting in more insight.

00:04:40.680 --> 00:04:43.660
And I've made a lot of
mileage in my career

00:04:43.660 --> 00:04:46.760
on these sorts of
scaling arguments.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:52.130
OK, so helium-- the
notes are beautiful.

00:04:52.130 --> 00:04:53.980
They're written by Troy.

00:04:53.980 --> 00:04:55.780
And they're very long.

00:04:55.780 --> 00:04:59.830
And they're very
correct and incisive.

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:03.700
And even if I weren't sick, I
couldn't cover all those notes.

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:08.590
So I'm going to make a rather
express trip through the notes.

00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:15.050
And the critical thing
is we have two electrons.

00:05:15.050 --> 00:05:19.270
And so we can't simply
solve the problem

00:05:19.270 --> 00:05:24.750
by using hydrogenic functions,
although we would like to.

00:05:24.750 --> 00:05:28.020
And the crucial
thing that is missing

00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:32.580
is if we could ignore the
interactions between the two

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:37.120
electrons, which
are enormous, then

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:38.980
we would be using
hydrogenic functions,

00:05:38.980 --> 00:05:41.590
and everything would be fine.

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:43.090
So we can't.

00:05:43.090 --> 00:05:47.050
And we use what's called
the independent electron

00:05:47.050 --> 00:05:52.390
approximation, where we're
still using hydrogenic orbitals

00:05:52.390 --> 00:05:55.990
and energies, but
we're using those

00:05:55.990 --> 00:06:00.400
to include the first
order perturbation

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:05.160
correction to the energies.

00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:09.000
So there's a term, the
interelectron repulsion

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.360
that leads to this
extra correction energy.

00:06:12.360 --> 00:06:14.560
And that's most
of the difference.

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:19.280
But then, we have
identical particles.

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:23.980
And when we have
identical particles,

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:27.500
the permutation of
those two particles

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:29.560
has to commute with
the Hamiltonian

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:31.820
because the Hamiltonian
only knows that we're

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:33.270
dealing with all the electrons.

00:06:33.270 --> 00:06:35.840
It doesn't put names on
the individual electrons.

00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:38.090
And so there's a
permutation symmetry

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:40.930
that has to be imposed.

00:06:40.930 --> 00:06:44.680
And this is very subtle because
the permutation symmetry has

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:47.670
nothing to do with
the energy, but it has

00:06:47.670 --> 00:06:51.110
to do with the energy states.

00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:53.480
And so we'll explore that.

00:06:53.480 --> 00:06:56.180
Now, since we're
going to be dealing

00:06:56.180 --> 00:06:59.330
with more than one electron,
there's a lot of symbols

00:06:59.330 --> 00:07:01.550
that we're going to
be carrying around.

00:07:01.550 --> 00:07:04.122
And so there's a
useful thing called

00:07:04.122 --> 00:07:08.900
the atomic units, which sets
most of the physical constants

00:07:08.900 --> 00:07:11.160
to 1.

00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:14.310
And that means all of the rubble
that you have to carry around

00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:15.780
goes away.

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:19.620
And it's not a big
deal because if you

00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:26.510
use all of the things in your
calculation in atomic units,

00:07:26.510 --> 00:07:31.730
namely value 1 or something
like 1, then at the end,

00:07:31.730 --> 00:07:34.370
you're going to get the
energy in atomic units.

00:07:34.370 --> 00:07:36.720
And we know what that is
in conventional units.

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:40.400
So it's a risky thing
because you don't really

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:42.180
know what you're doing.

00:07:42.180 --> 00:07:45.410
But at the end, you
can probably convert

00:07:45.410 --> 00:07:49.680
your number, which is a pure
number, into an actual energy.

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:55.390
OK, so let me start
with the good news.

00:07:58.610 --> 00:08:02.990
Well, maybe I should
leave this exposed.

00:08:02.990 --> 00:08:07.400
The good news is we have
two particles for helium--

00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:16.340
vector r, momentum, momentum
p vector for particle 1,

00:08:16.340 --> 00:08:20.300
vector, momentum.

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:23.370
OK, so these are the actors.

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:26.580
And when do we have to
worry about commutation

00:08:26.580 --> 00:08:27.750
or non-commutation?

00:08:30.570 --> 00:08:35.090
Well, the answer
is the coordinates

00:08:35.090 --> 00:08:40.500
associated with
different particles,

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:42.799
they contribute to the energy.

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:44.860
But there is no
problem of commutation.

00:08:44.860 --> 00:08:49.580
The momenta don't also commute.

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:52.140
The coordinate for
particle 1 and the momentum

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:55.700
for particle 2, they commute.

00:08:55.700 --> 00:09:03.950
The only things that doesn't
commute is r1x, p1x--

00:09:03.950 --> 00:09:07.100
those kinds of things.

00:09:07.100 --> 00:09:09.530
They're commutators
ih bar, and that

00:09:09.530 --> 00:09:11.610
means there's some problems.

00:09:11.610 --> 00:09:15.770
So most of the variables
are commuting variables,

00:09:15.770 --> 00:09:17.850
but some are not.

00:09:17.850 --> 00:09:21.260
And you have to deal with that.

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:21.760
OK.

00:09:24.550 --> 00:09:27.880
We know that if we
have, as, for example,

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:30.310
in a three-dimensional
harmonic oscillator,

00:09:30.310 --> 00:09:33.550
if we have a Hamiltonian
that doesn't commute--

00:09:33.550 --> 00:09:37.180
if we can divide the
system up into parts, then

00:09:37.180 --> 00:09:40.630
the Hamiltonian for each part
commutes with the Hamiltonian

00:09:40.630 --> 00:09:43.300
for the other part,
which is part of this.

00:09:43.300 --> 00:09:45.790
Then, you can write
the Hamiltonian

00:09:45.790 --> 00:09:49.300
as a sum of individual
system Hamiltonians

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:53.580
that commute with each other,
the energies as the sum,

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:55.817
and the wave functions
as the product.

00:09:55.817 --> 00:09:56.650
And so we like that.

00:09:56.650 --> 00:09:59.770
And we'd like to be able to
build a picture for helium that

00:09:59.770 --> 00:10:02.090
is like that.

00:10:02.090 --> 00:10:05.770
And so if we write the
Hamiltonian for helium,

00:10:05.770 --> 00:10:13.660
we have p squared for particle
1 over to me with p squared--

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:14.720
I don't know.

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:15.820
Le me see.

00:10:15.820 --> 00:10:17.590
Let me organize better.

00:10:23.610 --> 00:10:33.620
Minus zb squared over
4 pi epsilon 0 r1.

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:43.100
And then we have another term
like this for particle 2.

00:10:43.100 --> 00:10:47.489
And we can call
this Hamiltonian 1.

00:10:47.489 --> 00:10:50.210
I don't want to do that.

00:10:50.210 --> 00:10:54.910
Hamiltonian 1, and
this Hamiltonian 2.

00:10:54.910 --> 00:10:57.670
And these are hydrogen
atom Hamiltonians.

00:10:57.670 --> 00:11:00.030
And we know
everything about them.

00:11:00.030 --> 00:11:03.030
So it's a fantastic
way to build up

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:08.960
a basis set consisting of
energy, zero-order energies

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:11.810
and zero-order wave
functions, with which

00:11:11.810 --> 00:11:14.240
we can calculate anything.

00:11:14.240 --> 00:11:17.270
And so then we have
this one other term,

00:11:17.270 --> 00:11:27.390
which plus e squared
over 4 pi epsilon 0

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:32.070
over 1 minus r minus r2 vectors.

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:37.620
That's the bad news.

00:11:41.110 --> 00:11:45.790
This says we have a
Hamiltonian, where

00:11:45.790 --> 00:11:50.260
we can't use the eigenvalues
and eigenfunctions

00:11:50.260 --> 00:11:57.430
of the hydrogenic things unless
we do-- so we can say, well,

00:11:57.430 --> 00:12:02.350
these give the first-order
energies for whatever state

00:12:02.350 --> 00:12:05.235
we want.

00:12:05.235 --> 00:12:10.710
But we can calculate matrix
elements of this term

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:15.020
in the basis set
associated with hydrogen.

00:12:15.020 --> 00:12:16.420
And that's fine.

00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:19.250
That's a perfectly
good way to calculate

00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:21.990
the first-order
correction to the energy.

00:12:21.990 --> 00:12:24.855
But what about this?

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:29.440
When we do perturbation
theory and calculate

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:34.050
the second-order
corrections to the energy,

00:12:34.050 --> 00:12:35.105
what is that usually?

00:12:42.620 --> 00:12:45.350
Maybe I didn't ask the
question clearly enough.

00:12:45.350 --> 00:12:50.110
What do you have to do to get
these second-order energies

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:54.360
in an infinite
dimension problem?

00:12:54.360 --> 00:12:57.120
I just gave it away.

00:12:57.120 --> 00:13:02.260
Somebody has to have the
courage to say something here.

00:13:02.260 --> 00:13:13.514
Remember, we have a sum of n not
equal to n from 0 to infinity.

00:13:13.514 --> 00:13:14.410
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:15.880
PROFESSOR: That's it.

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:18.280
OK, I encouraged you.

00:13:18.280 --> 00:13:24.100
So the way we could use this
basis set in a perturbation

00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:27.340
theory format is to
calculate an infinite number

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:30.100
of off-diagonal matrix
elements of the hydrogenic wave

00:13:30.100 --> 00:13:32.410
functions.

00:13:32.410 --> 00:13:36.630
And that could yield
results, but it's not

00:13:36.630 --> 00:13:39.070
the way it's done usually.

00:13:39.070 --> 00:13:40.740
There's a variational
calculation

00:13:40.740 --> 00:13:44.080
that you use to get the
better wave functions.

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:46.050
But we're not going
to do that here.

00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:48.240
We're going to go
as far as we can

00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:53.370
without actually addressing
what's wrong if we stop here.

00:13:58.730 --> 00:14:07.270
OK, so this guy is h1,
the source of all trouble.

00:14:07.270 --> 00:14:11.330
And how we deal with it
is there are three steps.

00:14:11.330 --> 00:14:13.710
One is ignore it.

00:14:13.710 --> 00:14:19.200
The other is use our
hydrogenic functions

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:26.150
to calculate matrix elements
of this and get an h1, an e1.

00:14:26.150 --> 00:14:28.730
And the third step would
be to get the exact answer

00:14:28.730 --> 00:14:33.310
by doing an infinitely
difficult calculation, OK?

00:14:36.030 --> 00:14:36.530
All right.

00:14:39.890 --> 00:14:44.810
So this is going to be a
notational voyage, which

00:14:44.810 --> 00:14:47.240
is horrible.

00:14:47.240 --> 00:14:50.990
Because we have many particles,
and particles have coordinates

00:14:50.990 --> 00:14:55.440
and spins, we're going to
have an explosion of stuff,

00:14:55.440 --> 00:14:58.970
even if we get rid of
the extraneous units.

00:14:58.970 --> 00:15:01.040
But let's get rid of
the extraneous units.

00:15:01.040 --> 00:15:02.240
And so atomic units--

00:15:07.970 --> 00:15:11.330
we can choose any internally
consistent set of units

00:15:11.330 --> 00:15:12.430
we want.

00:15:12.430 --> 00:15:17.750
And in atomic units, we say that
the mass of the electron is 1.

00:15:17.750 --> 00:15:20.300
The charge of the electron is 1.

00:15:20.300 --> 00:15:23.960
The h bar is 1.

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:27.560
4 pi epsilon 0 is 1.

00:15:27.560 --> 00:15:28.520
That's good.

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:31.560
A lot of stuff just going away.

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:37.630
OK, and the energy in
atomic units is not 1.

00:15:37.630 --> 00:15:43.180
The energy in atomic
units is minus 2 times

00:15:43.180 --> 00:15:47.860
the energy of the
hydrogenic 1s orbital.

00:15:47.860 --> 00:15:53.440
And that comes out to
be 27.21 electron volts,

00:15:53.440 --> 00:15:56.780
in more convenient units.

00:15:56.780 --> 00:16:00.890
So you calculate a number, and
then you multiply it by this

00:16:00.890 --> 00:16:02.270
to get the real energy.

00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:10.500
OK, and the unit
of length is a0,

00:16:10.500 --> 00:16:14.070
which is the radius of the
n equals 1 hydrogenic Bohr

00:16:14.070 --> 00:16:17.970
orbital, or Bohr orbit.

00:16:17.970 --> 00:16:23.580
And that's 0.529 angstroms,
with a lot more digits if you

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:26.880
need them, OK?

00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:33.490
And the speed of light
is 137 in atomic units.

00:16:33.490 --> 00:16:37.380
So everything that
you're going to need

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:42.560
is either 1 or something
that is related to--

00:16:42.560 --> 00:16:46.590
OK, so you can do this,
and I don't like it

00:16:46.590 --> 00:16:51.141
because it's so easy
in a big calculation

00:16:51.141 --> 00:16:53.730
to get your units screwed up.

00:16:53.730 --> 00:16:56.730
But it's certainly
great for lecturing

00:16:56.730 --> 00:16:59.005
and perhaps for writing
computer programs.

00:17:04.730 --> 00:17:13.480
OK, so let's start with a
non-interacting electron

00:17:13.480 --> 00:17:14.380
approximation.

00:17:17.290 --> 00:17:23.359
And in the notes, it's
represented by these letters.

00:17:23.359 --> 00:17:25.520
I don't know
whether that this is

00:17:25.520 --> 00:17:31.940
Troy notation or widely-adopted
in quantum chemical circles.

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:34.670
But it's easier to
write this than that.

00:17:34.670 --> 00:17:39.520
And that just means we're
going to ignore this.

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:41.890
We just forget about it.

00:17:41.890 --> 00:17:45.790
Now, we know that's stupid
because the electrons have

00:17:45.790 --> 00:17:47.230
charge of 1.

00:17:47.230 --> 00:17:49.000
And they repel each other.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:52.465
And the nucleus has charge
of 2, in the case of helium.

00:17:55.660 --> 00:18:04.450
And so we know that this
term is rather similar to h0.

00:18:04.450 --> 00:18:07.960
And we can't expect to get very
far completely ignoring it.

00:18:07.960 --> 00:18:10.157
But we can do it, and
we can do a calculation,

00:18:10.157 --> 00:18:11.740
and we can find out
how well it works.

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:22.470
So first of all, it's
