00:22:52.480 --> 00:22:55.530
So we have this
mystical, or mythical,

00:22:55.530 --> 00:22:57.040
or whatever operator--

00:22:57.040 --> 00:23:04.410
p12 operating on some
function of r1 and r2.

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:08.730
And what it does is it
permutes the electrons.

00:23:11.490 --> 00:23:16.800
We know that if
something is operating

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:19.290
on the names of
the electrons, it

00:23:19.290 --> 00:23:23.100
has to commute with
the Hamiltonian.

00:23:23.100 --> 00:23:26.310
So that means that
this operator has

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:33.120
to have eigenvalues if these
states are eigenfunctions

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:35.780
of the Hamiltonian.

00:23:35.780 --> 00:23:38.330
And there are two
possible eigenvalues

00:23:38.330 --> 00:23:46.940
because we know p12 squared
on psi is equal to plus psi.

00:23:46.940 --> 00:23:49.820
So the only way you
can do that is having

00:23:49.820 --> 00:23:52.880
the eigenvalue of the
permutation operator

00:23:52.880 --> 00:23:57.390
be either plus 1 or minus 1.

00:23:57.390 --> 00:23:59.360
And this is a
fundamental symmetry.

00:23:59.360 --> 00:24:03.710
And I can't possibly tell
you where it comes from

00:24:03.710 --> 00:24:06.150
or what I'm about to write
on the board comes from.

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:25.620
But so all half integer
spins correspond

00:24:25.620 --> 00:24:36.434
to antisymmetry or belong
to the eigenvalue minus 1.

00:24:36.434 --> 00:24:37.600
And they're called fermions.

00:24:42.560 --> 00:24:47.340
And integer spins are
symmetric with permutations.

00:24:47.340 --> 00:24:58.760
And so integer or symmetric,
and they're bosons.

00:25:02.140 --> 00:25:04.380
So we have to write
wave functions which

00:25:04.380 --> 00:25:08.300
are wave functions of
the electrons, which

00:25:08.300 --> 00:25:11.270
are antisymmetric with
respect to the permutation

00:25:11.270 --> 00:25:14.280
of every pair of electrons.

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:16.040
So helium, we only
have two electrons.

00:25:16.040 --> 00:25:18.670
It's not so bad.

00:25:18.670 --> 00:25:20.840
But when you think
about something

00:25:20.840 --> 00:25:23.510
like carbon monoxide,
which I always think about,

00:25:23.510 --> 00:25:25.640
or some other
molecule where there's

00:25:25.640 --> 00:25:28.460
more than two electrons,
there's a God awful number

00:25:28.460 --> 00:25:30.410
of permutations.

00:25:30.410 --> 00:25:33.740
And you have to build them
all into the wave function.

00:25:33.740 --> 00:25:38.510
And the normal feeling
when you hear that is,

00:25:38.510 --> 00:25:43.590
oh, no, I can't possibly
imagine how to do that.

00:25:43.590 --> 00:25:47.180
And if I could, there would be
a ridiculous number of integrals

00:25:47.180 --> 00:25:50.770
that I would have to evaluate.

00:25:50.770 --> 00:25:52.850
And it's true.

00:25:52.850 --> 00:25:54.890
There are a ridiculous
number of integrals.

00:25:54.890 --> 00:25:58.280
But there is a simple
algebra that enables you

00:25:58.280 --> 00:26:00.440
how to deal with them.

00:26:00.440 --> 00:26:05.310
And it involves using what is
called Slater determinantal

00:26:05.310 --> 00:26:06.140
wave functions.

00:26:08.639 --> 00:26:09.680
And I'll talk about that.

00:26:09.680 --> 00:26:12.430
Slater was an MIT professor.

00:26:12.430 --> 00:26:14.120
He wrote a lot of books.

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:17.250
But the thing-- integer.

00:26:17.250 --> 00:26:20.820
Oh, they'res sort of a t.

00:26:20.820 --> 00:26:23.050
But the most
important thing he did

00:26:23.050 --> 00:26:26.020
was to develop
this way of dealing

00:26:26.020 --> 00:26:30.740
with an antisymmetric
electronic wave functions.

00:26:30.740 --> 00:26:33.640
So the next thing we
have to do is discover

00:26:33.640 --> 00:26:36.910
how do we build symmetric wave
functions for the simplest

00:26:36.910 --> 00:26:40.150
possible case where
there's two electrons?

00:26:40.150 --> 00:26:43.120
And already, we discover
some surprising consequences

00:26:43.120 --> 00:26:45.311
for this.

00:26:45.311 --> 00:26:46.810
And so I'm going
to go through this,

00:26:46.810 --> 00:26:48.430
but I'm going to
skip a lot of steps

00:26:48.430 --> 00:26:50.579
because it's so clearly
written in the notes

00:26:50.579 --> 00:26:52.120
and because we don't
really have time

00:26:52.120 --> 00:26:55.360
to deal with 15 pages
of single-spaced notes.

00:26:55.360 --> 00:27:02.567
And I'm not sufficiently at my
