00:39:50.350 --> 00:39:54.430
to a spatial part
and a spin part.

00:39:54.430 --> 00:39:57.090
Now, I'll make an
outrageous statement.

00:39:57.090 --> 00:39:59.400
Doesn't matter how
many electrons.

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:01.860
You'll always be
able to factor it

00:40:01.860 --> 00:40:05.980
into a spatial part
and a spin part.

00:40:05.980 --> 00:40:11.410
Now, what is necessary
is always this function

00:40:11.410 --> 00:40:13.740
has to be antisymmetric.

00:40:13.740 --> 00:40:15.670
And in this case,
it's the spatial part

00:40:15.670 --> 00:40:18.720
that's antisymmetric and the
spin part that's symmetric.

00:40:21.360 --> 00:40:24.095
Now, when we try to do
these two stick diagrams.

00:40:27.540 --> 00:40:32.290
we cannot write a correct
equation for this guy.

00:40:32.290 --> 00:40:34.630
We have to do both of them.

00:40:34.630 --> 00:40:36.940
We have to combine the two.

00:40:36.940 --> 00:40:39.820
And that will give us a
separated spin part and spatial

00:40:39.820 --> 00:40:41.260
part.

00:40:41.260 --> 00:40:43.180
And it's antisymmetric.

00:40:43.180 --> 00:40:48.170
You can't make in an asymmetric
function of this just switching

00:40:48.170 --> 00:40:49.565
the coordinates.

00:40:52.300 --> 00:40:54.770
And what you find
when you do this

00:40:54.770 --> 00:40:59.660
is going to be that
we get functions

00:40:59.660 --> 00:41:04.370
which look like alpha beta
plus or minus beta alpha.

00:41:07.180 --> 00:41:11.750
OK, so spin 1 alpha spin
2 beta plus or minus

00:41:11.750 --> 00:41:14.200
spin 1 beta spin 2 alpha.

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:29.040
And it turns out that there are
three spin functions that we

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:31.800
get, which are symmetric.

00:41:31.800 --> 00:41:34.920
And all three of
these are associated

00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:37.860
with this antisymmetric
spatial function.

00:41:37.860 --> 00:41:40.547
They have the same energy.

00:41:40.547 --> 00:41:42.880
And since they're three of
them, we call them a triplet.

00:41:46.930 --> 00:41:50.020
And since we're
talking about spins,

00:41:50.020 --> 00:41:53.080
this triplet corresponds
to s equals 1.

00:41:53.080 --> 00:41:56.680
You use s equals 1 and creation
and annihilation operators

00:41:56.680 --> 00:41:58.420
or raising and
lowering operators

00:41:58.420 --> 00:42:04.245
to show that these are, in fact,
the three eigenstates of s sub

00:42:04.245 --> 00:42:04.745
z.

00:42:07.600 --> 00:42:10.460
So we call it a triplet
because they're three of them.

00:42:10.460 --> 00:42:14.140
And it also corresponds
to s equals 1.

00:42:14.140 --> 00:42:19.570
And there's one, alpha
beta minus beta alpha,

00:42:19.570 --> 00:42:22.680
which is antisymmetric
and is associated

00:42:22.680 --> 00:42:27.430
with a different spatial
function, which is symmetric.

00:42:27.430 --> 00:42:29.830
And it has to have
a different energy

00:42:29.830 --> 00:42:33.640
because the Hamiltonian operates
on the spatial part and not

00:42:33.640 --> 00:42:34.930
on the spin part.

00:42:34.930 --> 00:42:37.690
So antisymmetry has
forced you to have

00:42:37.690 --> 00:42:41.020
two different spatial
wave functions,

00:42:41.020 --> 00:42:43.090
and that guarantees
that these guys

00:42:43.090 --> 00:42:45.640
will have different energies.

00:42:45.640 --> 00:42:51.070
And since there's only one of
them, we call it a singlet,

00:42:51.070 --> 00:42:52.690
and it corresponds
to s equals 0.

00:42:55.790 --> 00:42:59.420
So now, we want to know,
which is higher in energy,

00:42:59.420 --> 00:43:02.180
the singlet or the triplet?

00:43:02.180 --> 00:43:04.050
And how much higher?

00:43:04.050 --> 00:43:06.380
And so, again, we take
the wave functions

00:43:06.380 --> 00:43:08.900
that are correct as far as
permutation is concerned,

00:43:08.900 --> 00:43:13.100
but only approximate as far
as using hydrogenic functions,

00:43:13.100 --> 00:43:17.166
and we evaluate the relevant
terms in the Hamiltonian.

00:43:21.140 --> 00:43:24.980
OK, so we can forget
about the spin parts now.

00:43:24.980 --> 00:43:27.740
We know we're going to have
two different spatial wave

00:43:27.740 --> 00:43:28.250
functions.

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:30.776
And we're going to want
to calculate-- yes?

00:43:30.776 --> 00:43:32.650
AUDIENCE: For the top
state, [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:32.650 --> 00:43:35.737
both spins [INAUDIBLE]?

00:43:35.737 --> 00:43:36.820
PROFESSOR: That should be?

00:43:36.820 --> 00:43:39.160
AUDIENCE: Would that
also be s equals 0?

00:43:39.160 --> 00:43:40.160
PROFESSOR: I can't hear.

00:43:40.160 --> 00:43:42.030
I understand the last word.

00:43:42.030 --> 00:43:46.070
AUDIENCE: With the statement,
both spin be also s equals 0?

00:43:48.670 --> 00:43:50.060
PROFESSOR: No.

00:43:50.060 --> 00:43:51.170
Both spins up.

00:43:51.170 --> 00:43:54.620
The vector sum of
1/2 and 1/2 is 1.

00:43:54.620 --> 00:43:57.155
And so the total spin
is going to be 1.

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:03.940
And so we have 3--

00:44:03.940 --> 00:44:07.060
I mean, if we're
applying s minus--

00:44:07.060 --> 00:44:08.290
suppose we start with--

00:44:08.290 --> 00:44:11.100
AUDIENCE: I meant that the top
spin [INAUDIBLE] both spins.

00:44:15.382 --> 00:44:16.090
PROFESSOR: Sorry.

00:44:18.730 --> 00:44:20.800
I can't hear properly.

00:44:20.800 --> 00:44:23.216
AUDIENCE: The topmost state
with both spins on it?

00:44:23.216 --> 00:44:23.840
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:44:23.840 --> 00:44:27.270
AUDIENCE: Would that have
s equals 0 or s equals 1?

00:44:27.270 --> 00:44:29.630
PROFESSOR: It has s equals 1.

00:44:29.630 --> 00:44:31.600
OK.

00:44:31.600 --> 00:44:35.920
And now, I don't want to go
into the angular momentum matrix

00:44:35.920 --> 00:44:36.420
element.

00:44:36.420 --> 00:44:39.100
That would be the last
thing in this lecture.

00:44:39.100 --> 00:44:44.590
So yes, the projection
quantum numbers

00:44:44.590 --> 00:44:48.640
are not uniquely associated
with the total spin.

00:44:48.640 --> 00:44:52.680
But if you have alpha alpha, you
can show that it's s equals 1.

00:44:52.680 --> 00:44:56.250
And alpha beta plus
beta alpha is 1.

00:44:56.250 --> 00:44:58.600
And beta beta is 1.

00:44:58.600 --> 00:45:02.740
But alpha beta minus
beta alpha is spin 0.

00:45:02.740 --> 00:45:05.740
You can do that using creation
and annihilation operators.

00:45:05.740 --> 00:45:08.860
It's clear, OK?

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:11.470
So you have to take
it on faith until you

00:45:11.470 --> 00:45:13.520
prove what I've just said.

00:45:13.520 --> 00:45:16.510
And it takes about two minutes.

00:45:16.510 --> 00:45:22.240
OK, so we can evaluate
the integrals.

00:45:22.240 --> 00:45:27.330
And something very
beautiful occurs.

00:45:27.330 --> 00:45:30.830
And it's done very, very
clearly in the notes.

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:33.710
And it would take me more time
than we have left to do it,

00:45:33.710 --> 00:45:35.450
and I didn't plan
on doing it anyway.

00:45:35.450 --> 00:45:40.880
So we get the energies for the
singlet and triplet states,

00:45:40.880 --> 00:45:47.720
which are E 1s plus E 2s.

00:45:50.240 --> 00:45:53.730
Now, remember, these are
for a 1s orbital on helium,

00:45:53.730 --> 00:45:57.230
so it's going to be
four times the energy

00:45:57.230 --> 00:46:00.710
of the 1s orbital on hydrogen.
But we know what they are.

00:46:00.710 --> 00:46:08.390
Plus what we call J 1s2s
plus or minus K 1s2s.

00:46:11.480 --> 00:46:13.910
So this is clear.

00:46:13.910 --> 00:46:16.130
And the integral
associated with this

00:46:16.130 --> 00:46:18.810
is taking the square
of the wave function.

00:46:18.810 --> 00:46:21.740
And basically, we're
evaluating the interaction

00:46:21.740 --> 00:46:31.070
between an electron 1 in the
1s orbital and electron 2

00:46:31.070 --> 00:46:32.130
in the 2s orbital.

00:46:32.130 --> 00:46:34.220
So that's a perfectly
doable thing.

00:46:34.220 --> 00:46:35.610
It's a classical quantity.

00:46:35.610 --> 00:46:37.660
We have two charged
distributions,

00:46:37.660 --> 00:46:40.640
and we're calculating
the energy interaction

00:46:40.640 --> 00:46:44.480
between two electrons in these
two charged distributions.

00:46:44.480 --> 00:46:46.670
So this is called
the Coulomb integral.

00:46:49.490 --> 00:46:53.440
And that is an entirely
classical quantity.

00:46:53.440 --> 00:46:56.550
And this is called
the exchange integral.

00:46:59.340 --> 00:47:02.520
And the reason we call it
an exchange integral is,

00:47:02.520 --> 00:47:04.260
basically, we're
switching the electrons

00:47:04.260 --> 00:47:06.300
between the two orbitals.

00:47:06.300 --> 00:47:10.050
And this is something which is
entirely quantum mechanical.

00:47:10.050 --> 00:47:13.890
It comes about because of
the permutation symmetry

00:47:13.890 --> 00:47:16.650
that's required for fermions.

00:47:16.650 --> 00:47:19.560
And so this is the surprise.

00:47:19.560 --> 00:47:23.250
And it also depends
on whether you

00:47:23.250 --> 00:47:25.740
have a symmetric,
or an antisymmetric,

00:47:25.740 --> 00:47:27.960
or a single, or a triplet.

00:47:27.960 --> 00:47:29.760
And so you end up
getting an energy level

00:47:29.760 --> 00:47:32.880
diagram for the state of
a configuration, which

00:47:32.880 --> 00:47:33.970
looks like this.

00:47:33.970 --> 00:47:37.570
So we start out with E 0 1s2s.

00:47:40.710 --> 00:47:44.700
And then we allow the charged
distributions to interact.

00:47:44.700 --> 00:47:46.980
And the electrons are
going to repel each other.

00:47:46.980 --> 00:47:49.030
It's a positive energy.

00:47:49.030 --> 00:47:58.870
And so this is E 0 plus J. And
then, we include the exchange

00:47:58.870 --> 00:48:00.970
interaction.

00:48:00.970 --> 00:48:03.520
And so this is
the difference 2K.

00:48:03.520 --> 00:48:13.880
And this is E0 plus J plus K.
And this is E0 plus J minus K.

00:48:13.880 --> 00:48:16.840
And this is the triplet state.

00:48:19.740 --> 00:48:20.750
And this is a singlet.

00:48:24.330 --> 00:48:28.810
And for helium, we
call the singlet state

00:48:28.810 --> 00:48:35.550
singlet s because total
angular momentum is 0.

00:48:35.550 --> 00:48:39.570
And spin, it has 0.

00:48:39.570 --> 00:48:42.180
And the triplet we
call a triplet s.

00:48:42.180 --> 00:48:49.300
Now, if we did 1s 2p, we would
get singlet and triplet p

00:48:49.300 --> 00:48:49.800
states.

00:48:53.780 --> 00:48:56.420
But the important
thing is, how big is K?

00:48:56.420 --> 00:48:59.810
And remember, K is
an approximation.

00:48:59.810 --> 00:49:04.100
It's a real quantity, but
for hydrogenic orbitals,

00:49:04.100 --> 00:49:05.420
it's going to be incorrect.

00:49:11.490 --> 00:49:22.820
And so 2K 12 is
2.4 electron volts.

00:49:22.820 --> 00:49:24.770
And that's a perfectly
doable calculation

00:49:24.770 --> 00:49:26.900
because you're dealing
with simple functions.

00:49:26.900 --> 00:49:28.400
And you can do this integral.

00:49:28.400 --> 00:49:30.710
And you can actually
do it in closed form.

00:49:30.710 --> 00:49:32.960
But it's 2.4 electron volts.

00:49:32.960 --> 00:49:45.110
And experiment, it's 0.8.

00:49:45.110 --> 00:49:48.630
And this tells you
something really important.

00:49:48.630 --> 00:49:52.320
The repulsion between
two electrons,

00:49:52.320 --> 00:49:55.440
when you have the
correct wave function,

00:49:55.440 --> 00:50:01.350
is less than it would be if
you're using the wrong wave

00:50:01.350 --> 00:50:02.120
functions.

00:50:04.940 --> 00:50:08.900
And basically, whenever you do
anything using the wrong wave

00:50:08.900 --> 00:50:11.570
functions, your energy
levels are too large

00:50:11.570 --> 00:50:14.480
or the energy differences
are too large.

00:50:14.480 --> 00:50:16.990
And in this case, the electrons.

00:50:16.990 --> 00:50:19.490
And when you solve the
exact Schrodinger equation,

00:50:19.490 --> 00:50:24.220
the electrons know about how to
absorb it to avoid each other.

00:50:24.220 --> 00:50:26.200
It's called correlation energy.

00:50:26.200 --> 00:50:29.960
And this is what makes all the
calculations hard because there

00:50:29.960 --> 00:50:33.830
is no closed form analytic
expression for the correlation

00:50:33.830 --> 00:50:34.670
energy.

00:50:34.670 --> 00:50:40.280
And the way you optimize
the correlation energy

00:50:40.280 --> 00:50:43.850
is throwing a huge basis
set at the problem.

00:50:43.850 --> 00:50:46.610
And this is why it takes a long.

00:50:46.610 --> 00:50:49.450
And you never know that you've
converged until you fill

00:50:49.450 --> 00:50:52.990
in another million functions.

00:50:52.990 --> 00:50:55.150
OK, but so there
are several lessons.

00:50:55.150 --> 00:51:01.510
And that is we have something
that's completely classical,

00:51:01.510 --> 00:51:03.970
and we understand what it is.

00:51:03.970 --> 00:51:06.100
And then, we have
this extra thing

00:51:06.100 --> 00:51:08.905
that is a consequence of
the permutation symmetry.

00:51:11.430 --> 00:51:15.660
And so this extra thing
we calculated too big.

00:51:15.660 --> 00:51:19.320
But it says that
if we have states

00:51:19.320 --> 00:51:22.540
that belong to the same
electronic configuration--

00:51:22.540 --> 00:51:26.670
in other words, if we specify
the orbitals that are occupied,

00:51:26.670 --> 00:51:29.160
there's going to be more
than one electronic state.

00:51:31.820 --> 00:51:35.090
And so configurations split
into many different electronic

00:51:35.090 --> 00:51:35.900
states.

00:51:35.900 --> 00:51:38.840
And we know the machinery
that enables us to calculate

00:51:38.840 --> 00:51:41.090
their relative energies.

00:51:41.090 --> 00:51:44.620
And some of it is
simple Coulomb's law.

00:51:44.620 --> 00:51:46.930
And some of it is
something that's

00:51:46.930 --> 00:51:51.210
caused by the required
permutation symmetry.

00:51:51.210 --> 00:51:52.290
So I'm over time.

00:51:52.290 --> 00:51:55.590
But I can't believe
that I got to this point

00:51:55.590 --> 00:51:59.250
because I delivered everything
that was really important.

00:51:59.250 --> 00:52:02.520
When we have more than two
electrons, everything I've said

00:52:02.520 --> 00:52:05.340
is true, it's just
more complicated.

00:52:05.340 --> 00:52:09.690
And we have to evaluate
matrix elements

00:52:09.690 --> 00:52:13.650
between determinantal
wave functions, which

00:52:13.650 --> 00:52:16.620
looks like, if you
have n electrons,

00:52:16.620 --> 00:52:20.580
there's n factorial
terms in a determinate.

00:52:20.580 --> 00:52:23.290
And we have n factor l
squared matrix elements.

00:52:23.290 --> 00:52:24.540
And you don't want to do that.

00:52:24.540 --> 00:52:26.820
But there turns out to
be a simple algebra that

00:52:26.820 --> 00:52:31.740
makes it all pop out, almost
with the same level of effort

00:52:31.740 --> 00:52:32.940
as this.

00:52:32.940 --> 00:52:35.190
And so we'll talk about
many electron atoms,

00:52:35.190 --> 00:52:36.660
and then we'll go
on to molecules

00:52:36.660 --> 00:52:39.600
after the many
electron atoms lecture.

00:52:39.600 --> 00:52:41.150
OK.

